<item>
  <title>Querying Google’s Open Knowledge Format from R</title>
  <dc:creator>Travis Jakel</dc:creator>
  <link>https://travisjakel.github.io/okf-blog/posts/okf-r-duckdb/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<p>In June 2026, Google Cloud published the <a href="https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/knowledge-catalog">Open Knowledge Format (OKF)</a> — a vendor-neutral way to represent the curated knowledge that AI agents need as context. The format is refreshingly boring: <strong>a directory of markdown files with YAML frontmatter</strong>, one “concept” per file, with markdown links forming a graph. If you can <code>cat</code> a file, you can read OKF.</p>
<p>That minimalism is the point — but it leaves a gap. Google shipped a <em>producer</em> (an agent that turns BigQuery tables into OKF) and an HTML <em>visualizer</em>, and the community quickly added validators. What was missing was a way to <strong>load an OKF bundle into something you can actually query</strong> — and nothing existed in R at all.</p>
<p>So I wrote <a href="https://github.com/travisjakel/okf-ingest"><strong>okf-ingest</strong></a>, an R + Python package that reads a bundle, validates it, loads it into a portable <strong>DuckDB</strong> catalog, and lets you <strong>semantically search</strong> it. This post walks the R side end to end. (Disclosure: it’s my package.)</p>
<section id="what-an-okf-bundle-looks-like" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="what-an-okf-bundle-looks-like">What an OKF bundle looks like</h2>
<p>A concept file is just frontmatter + markdown:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb1" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode markdown code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode markdown"><span id="cb1-1"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">---</span></span>
<span id="cb1-2"><span class="an" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">type:</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"> Metric</span></span>
<span id="cb1-3"><span class="an" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">title:</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"> "Revenue"</span></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><span class="an" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">description:</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"> "Total order value over a period."</span></span>
<span id="cb1-5"><span class="an" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">tags:</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"> [finance, kpi]</span></span>
<span id="cb1-6"><span class="an" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">timestamp:</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"> 2026-06-21T00:00:00Z</span></span>
<span id="cb1-7"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">---</span></span>
<span id="cb1-8"></span>
<span id="cb1-9"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># Revenue</span></span>
<span id="cb1-10"></span>
<span id="cb1-11">Computed from <span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">[</span><span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">orders</span><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">](/orders.md)</span>.</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>The only field OKF <em>requires</em> is <code>type</code> — and it’s a free string, not an enum, because consumers must tolerate unknown types. Everything else (<code>title</code>, <code>description</code>, <code>tags</code>, <code>timestamp</code>) is recommended. Links like <code>[orders](/orders.md)</code> are untyped edges that turn the folder into a graph.</p>
</section>
<section id="install" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="install">Install</h2>
<p><code>okf</code> is on <a href="https://travisjakel.r-universe.dev">R-universe</a>:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb2" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">install.packages</span>(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"okf"</span>, <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">repos =</span> <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">c</span>(</span>
<span id="cb2-2">  <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">travisjakel =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"https://travisjakel.r-universe.dev"</span>,</span>
<span id="cb2-3">  <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">CRAN        =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"https://cloud.r-project.org"</span></span>
<span id="cb2-4">))</span></code></pre></div></div>
</section>
<section id="validate-permissively" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="validate-permissively">Validate, permissively</h2>
<p>OKF’s conformance bar is deliberately tiny: every non-reserved <code>.md</code> file must have parseable frontmatter with a non-empty <code>type</code>. Everything else — missing recommended fields, broken links, unknown types — is a <em>finding</em>, never a rejection. <code>okf</code> follows that to the letter:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb3" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">library</span>(okf)</span>
<span id="cb3-2"></span>
<span id="cb3-3">rd  <span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_read</span>(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"store"</span>)          <span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># a bundle directory</span></span>
<span id="cb3-4">val <span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_validate</span>(rd)</span>
<span id="cb3-5">val</span>
<span id="cb3-6"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;                 path severity        rule                              message</span></span>
<span id="cb3-7"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 1 metrics/revenue.md     warn broken_link unresolved link: /returns.md</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>One soft warning (a deliberately broken link in the example bundle), and the bundle is still conformant. A real linter would <code>stop()</code>; OKF says load what you can and report the rest.</p>
</section>
<section id="load-into-a-duckdb-catalog" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="load-into-a-duckdb-catalog">Load into a DuckDB catalog</h2>
<p><code>okf_ingest()</code> reads, validates, and writes everything into a DuckDB database:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb4" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1">res <span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_ingest</span>(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"store"</span>, <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">db_path =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"kb.duckdb"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-2"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">str</span>(res<span class="sc" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">$</span>summary)</span>
<span id="cb4-3"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; List of 8</span></span>
<span id="cb4-4"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ n_files     : int 5</span></span>
<span id="cb4-5"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ n_concepts  : int 3        # index.md / log.md are reserved, not concepts</span></span>
<span id="cb4-6"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ n_conformant: int 3</span></span>
<span id="cb4-7"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ conformant  : logi TRUE</span></span>
<span id="cb4-8"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ errors      : int 0</span></span>
<span id="cb4-9"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ warnings    : int 1</span></span>
<span id="cb4-10"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ links_total : int 8</span></span>
<span id="cb4-11"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;  $ links_broken: int 1</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>From here it’s <em>just DuckDB</em> — four tables (<code>okf_bundle</code>, <code>okf_concept</code>, <code>okf_link</code>, <code>okf_validation</code>) you can hit with <code>DBI</code>:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb5" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb5-1"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">library</span>(DBI)</span>
<span id="cb5-2">con <span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">&lt;-</span> res<span class="sc" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">$</span>con</span>
<span id="cb5-3"></span>
<span id="cb5-4"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">dbGetQuery</span>(con, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"SELECT path, type, title FROM okf_concept WHERE NOT reserved"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb5-5"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;                 path           type    title</span></span>
<span id="cb5-6"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 1       customers.md BigQuery Table Customers</span></span>
<span id="cb5-7"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 2 metrics/revenue.md         Metric   Revenue</span></span>
<span id="cb5-8"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 3          orders.md BigQuery Table   Orders</span></span>
<span id="cb5-9"></span>
<span id="cb5-10"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># the concept graph</span></span>
<span id="cb5-11"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_graph_df</span>(con)[, <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">c</span>(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"src_path"</span>, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"dst_path"</span>, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"resolved"</span>)]</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Because the catalog is plain DuckDB, it’s queryable from R, Python, or the bare <code>duckdb</code> CLI — and it’s a single file you can ship.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-payoff-semantic-search" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-payoff-semantic-search">The payoff: semantic search</h2>
<p>This is where okf-ingest goes past the other tools. <code>okf_embed()</code> chunks each concept body and embeds it (by default with a local <a href="https://ollama.com">Ollama</a> <code>nomic-embed-text</code> model — no data leaves your machine, no API key), storing the vectors right in the catalog:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb6" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_embed</span>(con)            <span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># -&gt; number of chunks embedded</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Then <code>okf_rag()</code> embeds a query and ranks chunks by cosine similarity, using DuckDB’s <strong>native <code>list_cosine_similarity</code></strong> — no vector-database extension required:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb7" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb7-1"><span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_rag</span>(con, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"how is revenue computed?"</span>, <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">k =</span> <span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">3</span>)[, <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">c</span>(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"path"</span>, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"title"</span>, <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"score"</span>)]</span>
<span id="cb7-2"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt;                 path     title score</span></span>
<span id="cb7-3"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 1 metrics/revenue.md   Revenue 0.709</span></span>
<span id="cb7-4"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 2          orders.md    Orders 0.642</span></span>
<span id="cb7-5"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">#&gt; 3       customers.md Customers 0.478</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>The pluggable embedder is just a function of <code>texts</code> returning vectors, so swapping in an OpenAI client (or anything else) is a one-liner.</p>
</section>
<section id="ingest-straight-from-github" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="ingest-straight-from-github">Ingest straight from GitHub</h2>
<p>You don’t need the bundle on disk. <code>okf_ingest()</code> accepts a git URL or a tar/zip archive (local or remote); it clones/extracts to a temp dir, finds the bundle, and cleans up after itself:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb8" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode r code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1">res2 <span class="ot" style="color: #003B4F;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">okf_ingest</span>(</span>
<span id="cb8-2">  <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/knowledge-catalog.git"</span>,</span>
<span id="cb8-3">  <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">subdir  =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"okf/samples/bitcoin"</span>,     <span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># bundle within the repo</span></span>
<span id="cb8-4">  <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">db_path =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"bitcoin.duckdb"</span></span>
<span id="cb8-5">)</span></code></pre></div></div>
</section>
<section id="honest-scope" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="honest-scope">Honest scope</h2>
<p>OKF is two weeks old — “an invitation, not yet a standard.” And the <em>validate/lint</em> niche already has good tools (a Node validator, a pure-Rust crate). okf-ingest isn’t trying to be another linter. It’s the only tool that turns a bundle into a <strong>SQL-queryable, semantically-searchable DuckDB catalog</strong>, and the only one with R (and Python) bindings — which is exactly the gap if you live in the tidy/DuckDB/arrow world.</p>
<p>If you’re experimenting with agent context, knowledge bases, or just want a tidy way to query a folder of markdown, give it a spin:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Repo:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/travisjakel/okf-ingest" class="uri">https://github.com/travisjakel/okf-ingest</a></li>
<li><strong>OKF spec:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/knowledge-catalog" class="uri">https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/knowledge-catalog</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Issues and PRs welcome.</p>


</section>

